<div class="light-borderblock">
{{Image Banner|image=SpeakerWall.webp|caption=Heavy decibels pierce your ears...}}
{{Quote|My ears became overwhelmed by the noise emanating all around me. Covering them with my fingers barely did anything; the pain wanted me to scream in this stereo madness...}}
{{Alt Class|no=109|ext=1|env=4|ent=1}}
</div>
<div class="light-borderblock">
<div align="center">
==<font size="6"><span style="background:#b7a58c; -webkit-background-clip:text !important; -webkit-text-fill-color:transparent">🎶 '''Description''' 🎶</span></font>==
</div>
{{Blurimage|file=RoomWithInstruments.jpg|caption=A room in '''Level 109''', featuring two [[Entity 2|innocuous windows]].|hovertext=Heavy decibels are playing out of my guitar.}}
'''Level 109''' is a series of living rooms, corridors, bedrooms and basements. Other floors, and by extension, stairs, are not present, making the level single story. Thus, rooms are arbitrarily placed and clumped together, which causes a claustrophobic environment.

The interior of '''Level 109''', including its walls, floors and ceilings, are in poor state, having various dents, scratches, holes, and being ripped in some places. In parts where there are holes, exposed electrical wiring emitting high voltage is uncommon; it is unadvised to tamper around with these wires or go near these holes, as they can fatally electrocute or burn the person. Moreover, erratically placed posters are frequent on these walls, covering up the imperfections on them. It is not rare to find heavily disorganized rooms in '''Level 109''', making the rooms resemble a near hoarder-like environment; not only does the untidy nature of the level further make the rooms more cramped, it is easy for one to trip and receive hefty injuries. Hence, watching one's steps and utilizing a flashlight in dingy areas is crucial for navigating certain areas in '''Level 109''' as to not fall victim to such injuries.

Found across '''Level 109''' is a myriad of instrumental equipment, namely guitars, drum sets, basses, amplifiers, microphones, speakers, keyboards, and occasionally, pianos. Along with these instruments are numerous instrumental accessories, cables, music stands, music sheets, record players with vinyl, noise-cancelling headphones, and various portable music players. Although the instruments are able to function and be played, instruments such as guitars can easily detune in just seconds of playing them. Additionally, these instruments are much more fragile and poorly built in quality; there have been numerous reports of guitar strings randomly snapping, holes being punched into drums by a drumstick, control knobs on amplifiers simply coming off, as well as piano keys being warped from slight presses.

The peculiarities do not end with the instruments; musical sheets are incoherent and realistically cannot be played; record players play vinyls at predetermined but incorrect speeds; and, portable music players contain seemingly random musical tracks that are incomprehensible sounds. Attempts to extract files from or add files to these portable music players have been fruitless, as every computer connected to these players thus far are unable to recognize these devices. [[Object 18|Kaboom-boxes]] and their white variants can also be infrequently found within the level; white kaboom-boxes in particular, though much rarer in appearance, can provide relief against the blasting environment of '''Level 109''' by temporarily silencing all noises for those in close proximity.
{{Blurimage|align=left|file=MusicInstrumentalRoom2.jpg|caption=A drum-set found in '''Level 109'''.|hovertext=We got vibrations coming up from the floor.}}
All instruments are anomalously amplified to produce extremely loud noises that linger around or exceed 100 decibels, even when played with the softest hands. Furthermore, the instruments are capable of emitting hefty vibrations on the level; although not enough to toss things around nor cause any more damage to the level, they can induce motion sickness within wanderers should the vibrations constantly occur for a prolonged period of time. Therefore, it is recommended that one refrains from playing any instrument in '''Level 109''', especially if they do not have the proper ear protection. The loud noise emitted by '''Level 109's''' instruments can result in instantaneous hearing loss without hearing protection.

Access to the outside is not possible, as the level lacks any normal windows or doors that lead to a supposed outside; however, one is able to hear perpetual precipitation should they move to a quieter room. This precipitation can be as gentle as light rain, to harsh downpour that is reported to sound akin to heavy knocking. At its worst, the precipitation can reach noise levels as high as 80 decibels; constant exposure to this loud rain after eight hours can also result in hearing loss. Lightning strikes, along with occasional gusts of wind, can additionally be heard emanating from the supposed outside. Nevertheless, the seemingly lack of impact these weather conditions have on the level itself have led many to speculate if these phenomena are simply auditory illusions.

Periodically, '''Level 109''' may inexplicably rock or roll, affecting everything within its confines. The magnitude of this turbulence may range from slight shaking, to sways that can toss objects not fixed into place. Thus, this explains why much of '''Level 109''' may appear messy and beaten up. Wanderers caught in the crossfire are subject to major injuries, with casualties being rare. Nonetheless, an approximate ten second warning is given in the form of harsh vibrations across the level, giving those time to exit '''Level 109''' or find a room that the person will not get tossed around in. Because of this turbulence, the air in '''Level 109''' is described to be dusty and hard to breathe in, resulting in irritation from one's nose, lungs, and eyes<ref>Flashlights confirm the dusty nature of '''Level 109's''' air, as one can see highly concentrated amounts of dust flying around in the light.</ref>. A pungent smell, described to reek of sweat by numerous wanderers, can be found near bedsheets, clothing or wardrobes.
{{Blurimage|file=AmpsInLiveRoom.jpg|caption=An image of a myriad of amps in '''Level 109'''.|hovertext=We're just listening to the rock that's giving too much noise. Are you deaf, you want to hear some more?}}
By far the most prominent hazard of '''Level 109''' is the extreme volume levels, most of which originate from the numerous amplifiers and speakers found throughout '''Level 109'''. Occasionally, speaker walls can be found blasting such noises as well, exacerbating the already deafening noise. The volume levels on these audio equipment cannot be adjusted in any way; the only method to disable them is by unplugging them. However, due to the cluttered nature of '''Level 109''', it is time-consuming and there is little incentive to manually track down and unplug each individual piece of equipment<ref>All electric equipment in '''Level 109''' is never found plugged together on the same extension cord.</ref>; not to mention, the lack of circuit breakers to completely shut off power in '''Level 109''' makes this task more challenging<ref>Because there are no circuit breakers in '''Level 109''', it consequently leads to isolated electrical fires, as well as for power outlets and plugged-in equipment to become damaged.</ref>. Even without accounting for any amplifiers or speakers, sources such as the supposed precipitation still produce considerably loud noise that becomes perilous after hours of continuous listening. The walls in between the rooms in '''Level 109''' have exceptional anomalous soundproofing, meaning each room in the level has its own set volume that does not spill over into the other rooms<ref>By extension, vibrations also cannot go through these walls.</ref>.

The music played in '''Level 109''' through the speakers is often a cacophony of instruments without any structure or pattern<ref>None of the music played in '''Level 109''' originates from the instruments in the level.</ref>. The lengths of these musical pieces are random, ranging from a few seconds to months at a time. Albeit, it is not uncommon for music<ref>The genres of music played can be identified as rock, metal, or grunge.</ref> from [[the Frontrooms]] to play along with the discord of sounds, notably being louder and more emphasized. Furthermore, all the musical files played in '''Level 109''' have been heavily compressed, resulting in a consistently loud signal that has little to no audio fidelity, audio distortions, and a fatiguing listening experience.
<div align="center">
==<font size="6"><span style="background:#b7a58c; -webkit-background-clip:text !important; -webkit-text-fill-color:transparent">🎶 '''Noise Properties''' 🎶</span></font>==
</div>
Most of the level averages out to around 100 to 110 dB—akin to a rock concert, a car horn, or certain portable music players at maximum volume. The quietest '''Level 109''' can get in certain rooms is only a still loud 80 dB; however, sudden bursts of sounds, usually from playing the instruments in '''Level 109''' or certain parts in the audio files being played in the level's speakers, can briefly reach volumes levels of 140 dB. For reference, 80 dB can be attributed to heavy city traffic, whilst noises around 140 db are comparable to a jackhammer, fireworks, a gunshot at close range<ref>Approximately 30 meters.</ref>, or a jet taking off at close range<ref>Approximately 25 meters.</ref>. This has the added effect of producing vibrations on the level; at the high end, this is enough to physically shake unfastened objects, as well as stimulate one's vestibular system in their inner ear (which is responsible for maintaining one's balance and sense of direction) to the point of feeling dizzy or nauseous.

At the quietest of '''Level 109''' (80 dB), continuous exposure can be for at most, eight hours, until hearing damage commences; around 110 dB, hearing damage occurs after thirty minutes; higher than ~120 dB, exposure is instantaneously detrimental. Regardless, unprotected hearing exposure to '''Level 109''' will eventually lead to noise-induced hearing loss (NIHL), with damage and death of one's hair cells in their inner ear. The stages for chronic noise-induced hearing loss are listed below:
*One's hearing will slowly be lost, typically unnoticeable or dismissed by the victim;
*Further continued exposure can lead to sounds become distorted, muffled, and the victim to experience tinnitus. 
Acoustic trauma<ref>Sudden bursts of loud noise around or exceeding 140 dB.</ref> can rupture one's eardrums, damage the bones in their middle ear, and permanently damage hair cells, resulting in immediate permanent hearing loss, tinnitus, or even complete deafness. Noise-induced hearing loss can be temporary, permanent, mild or severe, depending on how long one's listening exposure was. The side effects of noise-induced hearing loss, even after one equips protective hearing equipment or escapes '''Level 109''', include but are not limited to:
*Tinnitus;
*Fatigue;
*Stress and irritability;
*Anxiety;
*Sensitivity to hearing (hyperacusis);
*Depression;
*A feeling that one's ear is clogged;
*Increased blood pressure;
*Difficulty in concentrating;
*Difficulty in communicating;
*Insomnia;
*Increased heart rate.
Such side effects can be problematic to one's survival in the Backrooms, as not only will their cognitive abilities be greatly hindered, the hearing loss will make communication difficult and make it harder for them to stay alert.

As soon as one enters '''Level 109''' without any protective hearing equipment, the first course of action is to search for it, usually found scattered across the level; these come in the form of earplugs (blocking 15 to 33 dB), earmuffs (blocking 15 to 30 dB), and noise-cancelling headphones (blocking 20 to 40 dB of ambient sound in lower frequencies). Regardless, it is important to bear in mind that noise-cancelling headphones are far less effective in comparison to earplugs or earmuffs, as they cannot protect against higher pitched sounds or sudden loud sounds. It also should be noted that noise-cancelling headphones may sometimes be fully drained or at low battery, in which case they will provide limited insufficient protection. Moreover, if using earplugs, one must make sure that the earplugs are a perfect fit in ear canal, as to ensure the most effective airtight seal that is not uncomfortable. Nonetheless, wearing both earplugs and earmuffs provides the best protection in '''Level 109''', blocking an additional 10 to 15 dB when combined. All entrances documented to '''Level 109''' thus far only place one in rooms that are 80 to 110 dB loud, giving wanderers ample time to search for protective hearing equipment.

It is strongly advised to use the protective equipment sparingly; although '''Level 109''' is incomprehensibly ginormous—much like other levels in the Backrooms—certain areas, especially hotspots that are entrances from other levels, may run out of protective hearing equipment for newcomers to use. The main reason for these shortages is due to wanderers leaving the level with the hearing equipment on. In such case, one should return the equipment to an established outpost in some levels that contain an entrance or an exit to and from '''Level 109''' if possible.

As a result of the loud noise, normal talking between one another in '''Level 109''' is almost infeasible; not only does the loud noise drown out any human voices, the hearing protection that is advised for everyone to wear in '''Level 109''' will only further hinder oral communication. Therefore, communication methods like SMS or sign language are preferred in '''Level 109'''.
<div align="center">
==<font size="6"><span style="background:#b7a58c; -webkit-background-clip:text !important; -webkit-text-fill-color:transparent">🎶 '''Entities''' 🎶</span></font>==
</div>
Aside from [[Entity 2|innocuous windows]], the nature of '''Level 109''' poses an uninviting environment to most entities. However, viruses and bacteria are able to survive the level's environment, as the noise produced in the level only lingers in the audio frequency<ref>20 Hz to 20 kHz (20 000 Hz).</ref>, which generally does not affect such microscopic entities. Thus far, in addition to bacteria such as legionella (which may be found in '''Level 109's''' plumbing), [[carpetvirus]] has been reported in dingy sections (primarily mattresses and bedsheets), and the [[Hydrolitis Plague|hydrolitis plague]] may also be found in various containers that hold water.
<div align="center">
==<font size="6"><span style="background:#b7a58c; -webkit-background-clip:text !important; -webkit-text-fill-color:transparent">🎶 '''Addendum''' 🎶</span></font>==
</div>
<div class="titleblock"><span class="titlebox" style="color: white;">August 13, 2002</span>
<div align="center">
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<font size="6">'''Tamed Chaos'''</font>{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<font size="16"><span style="background:white; -webkit-background-clip:text !important; -webkit-text-fill-color:transparent">🎵</span></font>

I wandered off from my outpost in the [[Level 4|abandoned office]], where the complex of interconnecting corridors brought me to a dead end with an incongruous door. The light November rain grew stronger into pounding, and my surroundings shook like a party had been going on behind the door. It probably would have been better had I just retreated from something that I did not know about, but my curiosity took control of the best of me and directed me towards the door. I twisted the knob counterclockwise and gave it a big push; what I saw was an unbelievable mess of littered furniture, amps, wires, and guitars, along with an overwhelmingly noisy racket of instruments that immediately greeted me. It was like a music class goofing around before the teacher came in, only much louder.

I had to step into this world, one that was a huge juxtaposition from the otherwise near silence of the offices before me. Just I was ready to go back after taking a long observation of an enlarged teenager rock fan's disorganized room, the room spontaneously tilted to the right, bringing me and the clutter down with it and putting me to sleep. I was surprised to open my eyes not in [[The Void|the void]], but somewhere further deep in this labyrinth buried in with tossed chairs, guitars, wires, shelves, and bedsheets. The horrible smell of teen spirit flooded into my lungs, as if my other senses weren't already overwhelmed. The door I had originally entered this place from was nowhere in sight—I must have came across a completely different level.

Broken, beat and scarred, I dug myself out of the furniture landfill, and waiting for me was the same blasting mesmerizer of instruments, songs, and hammering rain. I wanted to cover my ears, but that only muffled the sounds. Each pluck from the basses and every strike onto the bass drums emitted from the various speakers shook me and the pile of furniture, making the pile mimic a speaker cover. Every hit from the drumsticks into the drums sent out a sound wave that knocked on my eardrums. 

In my treks through the Backrooms, noise was an important sign of some sort of presence against still spaces; it could be either an entity that has already heard you, or a hopeful indication of nearby wanderers—in other words, safety. Here in this speaker fortissimo, noise is reduced to meaninglessness; it is so abundant that it overtakes silence as the prominent background. Hell, silence becomes something that you would hear.

Just as my hearing began to fade, I was sent awake by an electric guitar that screamed against the discord of senseless instrumental noise. The strums, pull offs, sliding, and picking gave the guitar the impression that it was the voice of an entity, and it played with absolute passion. It was one of the best solos that my ears have ever laid on, only tainted by the prevalent noise around it. The screeches of the guitar disciplined the multitude of other playing instruments into a sort of rhythm. Whilst the chaotic musical piece still blistered my ears, at least it was by one that had structure to it rather than a disarray. The instruments were now not just playing out of whim, they were trying to achieve something; a disordered song, but one held under control by the sheer authority of the electric guitar's cries and wails.

Even though my tinnitus eventually drowned out and faded my surroundings, I found the beauty in such a dissonance. I like to think that the instruments were all alive; the electric guitar, despite the sheer din, took a stand against the crowd and revealed itself out loud, unwilling to conform into the dominant ongoing cacophony. I knew I could not stay any longer unless I wanted that to be the last thing I would ever hear, so I found my own way out whilst the show was happening. I may have been rendered with hearing loss for a while after my escape, but I have a rather fond memory of the clash of noises that felt so alive.

<font size="16"><span style="background:white; -webkit-background-clip:text !important; -webkit-text-fill-color:transparent">🎸</span></font>
</div></div>
<div align="center">
==<font size="6"><span style="background:#b7a58c; -webkit-background-clip:text !important; -webkit-text-fill-color:transparent">🎶 '''Colonies and Outposts''' 🎶</span></font>==
</div>
The nature of '''Level 109''' prohibits the establishment of long term colonies, notwithstanding the lack of incentive to settle in the level. Nonetheless, some outposts that are established in some levels that have an entrance to or an exit from the level (such as the [[Level 4#Colonies and Outposts|Society of the Red Cross in Level 4]]) may have stockpiles of protective hearing equipment for wanderers to either take or return equipment to.
<div align="center">
==<font size="6"><span style="background:#b7a58c; -webkit-background-clip:text !important; -webkit-text-fill-color:transparent">🎶 '''Entrances and Exits''' 🎶</span></font>==
</div>
{{Blurimage|file=TransitionToLevel0.jpeg|caption=An exit from '''Level 109''' that transitions to [[Level 0]].|hovertext=You hear exit music, for a film.}}
<div align="center">
==='''Entrances'''===
</div>
*Walking into a door found in numerous levels that is emitting loud music and hefty vibrations behind it, which offers a direct entrance;
*No-clipping into an instrument that can rarely be found in [[Level 82]];
*A random chance of clipping through the doorway of a Droid Factory in [[Level 754]].
<div align="center">
==='''Exits'''===
</div>
*Certain doors across '''Level 109''' are the most reliable exits, leading to a random level;
*Feeling the air quality becoming progressively worse indicates a smooth transition to a house in [[Level 38]];
*Hearing the music fade away into a slowed and pitched down cover of the song "Don't Worry, Be Happy" whilst wandering signifies a nearby doorway entrance to [[Level 81]];
*Under certain circumstances, wandering around '''Level 109''' can bring a wanderer to [[Level 0]].
*Losing all hearing may send one to [[Level 297]].
